\end_layout

\end_inset

Tax Farming Redux: Experimental Evidence on Performance Pay for Tax Collectors
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Khan et al 2016: Introduction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Focus on a bureaucrat (tax inspector) who has to assess, enforce, and audit
 property taxes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One possibility: sell the right to collect taxes to the bureaucrat and then
 let the bureaucrat keep most/all of the revenue: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Tax Farming
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 common throughout history (Rome, France etc.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But this is a setting where the bureaucrat and the citizen might collude.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
performance incentives affect division of rents without necessarily increasing
 revenue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
e.g.
 if collusion is costless, then performance pay increases bribes without
 increasing revenue since taxpayer now has to compensate the inspector for
 the foregone bonus.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Conduct an experiment in Punjab, Pakistan to investigate these issues.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Khan et al 2016: Setting
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Punjab population >80 million.
 Very low property tax collection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tax levied on the Gross Annual Rental Value (GARV) of the property.
 Determined by a formula with size of land and buildings as inputs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Different rates for owner-occupied and rental properties.
 And for residential and commercial.
 This is main way tax evasion happens.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tax administered in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

circles
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: geographic areas covering 2-10K houses.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Each circle has 3 officers: An 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inspector
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (boss) a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

clerk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (records) and a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (assists inspector)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Each year they send the taxpayer a bill.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Khan et al 2016: Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Taxpayer has true tax liability 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Inspector knows 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 but can choose to report 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}<\tau_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Inspector receives incentive payment 
\begin_inset Formula $r\tau_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Colluding to underreport is costly
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
taxpayer cost: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(\tau_{i}^{*}-\tau_{i}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
inspector cost: 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\left(\tau_{i}^{*}-\tau_{i}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Taxpayer and inspector Nash bargain over bribe 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If they don't agree a bribe, the taxpayer gets 
\begin_inset Formula $-\tau_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and the inspector gets 
\begin_inset Formula $r\tau_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If they agree, the taxpayer gets 
\begin_inset Formula $-\tau_{i}-\alpha_{i}\left(\tau_{i}^{*}-\tau_{i}\right)-b_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the inspector gets 
\begin_inset Formula $r\tau_{i}-\beta\left(\tau_{i}^{*}-\tau_{i}\right)+b_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Khan et al 2016: Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Joint surplus is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\underbrace{\tau_{i}^{*}-\tau_{i}-\alpha_{i}\left(\tau_{i}^{*}-\tau_{i}\right)-b_{i}}_{\text{taxpayer}}+\underbrace{r\left(\tau_{i}-\tau_{i}^{*}\right)-\beta_{i}\left(\tau_{i}^{*}-\tau_{i}\right)+b_{i}}_{\text{inspector}}\\
=\quad-\tau_{i}\left(1-\alpha_{i}-\beta_{i}-r\right)+\tau_{i}^{*}\left(1-\alpha_{i}-\beta_{i}-r\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Two cases
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{i}=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if }r+\alpha_{i}+\beta_{i}<1\\
\tau_{i}^{*} & \text{if }r+\alpha_{i}+\beta_{i}>1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With bargaining weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 on the taxpayer
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{i}=\left[\left(\beta_{i}+r\right)\gamma_{i}+\left(1-\gamma_{i}\right)\left(1-\alpha_{i}\right)\right]\tau_{i}^{*}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Khan et al 2016: Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
What happens to total revenue 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

? Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\alpha,\beta,\tau^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

 joint dist of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta,\tau^{*}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dT}{dr} & =\underset{r+\alpha+\beta=1,\tau^{*}\in\left(0,\infty\right)}{\int\int\int}\tau^{*}f\left(\alpha,\beta,\tau^{*}\right)d\alpha d\beta d\tau^{*}\\
 & =\underset{\alpha,\tau^{*}}{\int\int}\tau^{*}f\left(\alpha,1-r-\alpha,\tau^{*}\right)d\alpha d\tau^{*}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 the effect depends on how many people are on the margin between the two
 cases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Simplifying assumptions to note
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
linearity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{*}$
\end_inset

 known, no effort by bureaucrat
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
outside option is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{*}$
\end_inset

 so no extortion/overtaxation
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Khan et al 2016: Experiment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment 1: 
\emph on
Revenue
\emph default
 based performance pay:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Bonus}_{c}=\alpha_{c}\max\left\{ \text{Revenue}_{c}-\text{Benchmark}_{c},0\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Benchmark calculated from 3-year averages of historical collection plus
 normal rate of increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{c}$
\end_inset

 was 40% for lowest 50% of circles, 
\begin_inset Formula $30\%$
\end_inset

 between 50th and 75th percentiles, 20% at the top.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note incentive depends only on revenue, not whether it's more money from
 existing houses or finding new houses to bring into the tax net.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bonus divided 40%-30%-30% between inspector, constable & clerk.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
