Strengthening State Capabilities: The Role of Financial Incentives in the
 Call to Public Service
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dal B et al 2013: Introduction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
States need good people in order to function well.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 bureaucrats has many dimensions, how do pecuniary and non-pecuniary incentives
 of government jobs attract more or less of these dimensions?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Run an experiment inside Mexico's Regional Development Program to ask
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Do higher wages attract higher quality applicants?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Do higher wages allow the government to hire more people?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How do job location disadvantages affect recruitment?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dal B et al 2013: Context
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
2011: Regional Development Program (RDP) launched to increase state presence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Create network of 350 community development agents & 50 coordinators to
 identify needs in the community and report to federal government to get
 resources to meet demands.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Program implemented in 10 regions, 167 municipalities, 000s of localities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Each community development position is assigned to a particular municipality,
 selected on an index of socioeconomic characteristics.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dal B et al 2013: Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Employer faces a residual labor supply of large number of workers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
2 periods, no discounting.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Worker decides whether to incur cost 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 of attending interview for job with posted wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If worker interviewed, receives offer w/pr 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\in(0,1]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals differ in 2 ways:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Market quality 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 with distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(v\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Public Sector Motivation (PSM) 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in[0,\infty)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Utility from getting the job is 
\begin_inset Formula $w+\pi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In period 2, accept if better than market opportunity with value 
\begin_inset Formula $v+\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Shock 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\sim G\left(\varepsilon\right)$
\end_inset

 realized before getting the offer
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dal B et al 2013: Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Solve the model backwards: Workers will accept if 
\begin_inset Formula $v+\varepsilon\leq w+\pi$
\end_inset

.
 This happens w/pr 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(w+\pi-v\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Action in the entry decision will be driven by relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 2 cases:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 independent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $v=m\left(\pi\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is fixed (at 1).
 In particular, doesn't depend on type of the worker.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dal B et al 2013: Effects on Applicant Pool
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\shape smallcaps
proposition 1
\shape default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given the assumptions of our model, an increase in wages increases the size
 and average quality of the applicant pool.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the case where PSM and quality are independent in the population, an
 increase in wages decreases the average PSM of the applicant pool.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the case where PSM and quality are positively correlated according to
 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $m\left(\pi\right)$
\end_inset

, an increase in wages increases the average PSM of the applicant pool.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dal B et al 2013: Effects on Recruitment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Simplify: 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow\exists\bar{v}$
\end_inset

 type and all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\leq\bar{v}$
\end_inset

 attend the interview, 
\begin_inset Formula $v>\bar{v}$
\end_inset

 do not.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\bar{v}/\partial w>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Overall labor supplys at wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\int_{0}^{\bar{v}}G\left(w-v\right)f\left(v\right)dv=\underbrace{F\left(\bar{v}\right)}_{\text{applicant pool}}\underbrace{\int_{0}^{\bar{v}}G\left(w-v\right)\frac{f\left(v\right)}{F\left(\bar{v}\right)}dv}_{\gamma:\text{ conversion rate}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape smallcaps
proposition 2
\shape default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The measure of recruited candidates in our model, and the labor supplied
 to the firm in equilibrium, can be written as the product 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(\bar{v}\right)\gamma\left(w,\bar{v}\right)$
\end_inset

 of the applicant pool size and the conversion rate.
 Thus, the elasticity of labor supply facing the employer is 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\frac{dS}{sw}\frac{w}{S}=\frac{dF}{dw}\frac{w}{F}+\frac{d\gamma}{dw}\frac{w}{\gamma}\equiv\xi_{F\left(\bar{v}\right)}+\xi_{\gamma\left(w,\bar{v}\right)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Under the assumptions of the model, the elasticity of the applicant pool
 size is positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\xi_{F\left(\bar{v}\right)}>0\right)$
\end_inset

 while the sign of the elasticity of the conversion rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{\gamma\left(w,\bar{v}\right)}$
\end_inset

 is ambiguous
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dal B et al 2013: Experiment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

