\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ashraf et al 2018: Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Applicants choose between CHA and their outside option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Material benefits of being a CHA are 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals differ in ability 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and social preferences towards the community 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If work as CHA, produce health 
\begin_inset Formula $H\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 valued at 
\begin_inset Formula $sH\left(a\right)\Rightarrow U\left(s_{i}H\left(a_{i}\right),M\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Applying requires paying cost 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Probability of getting job is 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 (concave).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Outisde option is 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{a}>U_{a}>0\;\forall a$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Apply iff
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(a,s\right)=p\left(a\right)U\left(a,s\right)-c>V\left(a\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ashraf et al 2018: Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(0\right)<V\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then there's a threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{a}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}<\underline{a}$
\end_inset

 don't apply.
 If curvatures of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 suitable, then there's another threshold where 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\bar{a}\right)=V\left(\bar{a}\right)$
\end_inset

 and only 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{a}<a_{i}<\bar{a}$
\end_inset

 apply.
 Focus on this case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What happens when we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Higher ability people apply now
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Low ability applicants might be discouraged since less likely to get the
 job: 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial^{2}p/\partial a\partial M>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\shape smallcaps
result 1
\shape default
: 
\emph on
Increasing material benefits 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 will attract higher ability applicants who would not apply othersiwe 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\partial\bar{a}/\partial M>0\right)$
\end_inset

 and either (i) lower the ability of the lowest ranked applicant 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\partial\underline{a}/\partial M<0\right)$
\end_inset

 and increase the total number of applicants, or (ii) discourage low ability
 applicants 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\partial\underline{a}/\partial M>0\right)$
\end_inset

 and have an ambiguous impact on the total number of applicants.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ashraf et al 2018: Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{a}>U_{a}$
\end_inset

 the threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\left(s_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 will be increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{a}\left(s_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Talent and pro-sociality are positively correlated for highest ability applicant
s, and negatively correlated for lowst ability applicants, even when they're
 not correlated in the population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape smallcaps
result 2
\shape default
: 
\emph on
Under any 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the most able applicant is also the most prosocial.
 An increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 leaves the prosociality of the marginal applicant unchanged and has an
 ambiguous effect on the prosociality of the average applicant
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ashraf et al 2018: Applicants and Selection
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Recruitment drive 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 2,457 applications (average 7.3 for each position).
 1,804 met eligbility requirements, 1,585 came for interview and answered
 questionnaire.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use grade 12 (o-level) exam scores as ability measure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For non-cognitive skills, use career ambition (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what will you be doing in 5 years' time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

=
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

higher position in the Ministry
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For pro-sociality, use self-reported willingness to stay in the community
 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Inclusion of Others in Self (IOS)
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 scale
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Selection panels chose 2 candidates to serve as CHA in the posts.
 Panels = district health official, health post's health center representatice,
 3 members of the neighborhood health committee.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{ih}=\sum_{j\in J}\alpha_{j}^{c}C_{h}X_{i}^{j}+\sum_{j\in J}\alpha_{j}^{s}\left(1-C_{h}\right)X_{i}^{j}+\sum_{j\in J}\beta_{j}\bar{X}_{h}^{j}+\gamma N_{h}+\zeta_{ih}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ih}=1$
\end_inset

 if selected, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{h}=1$
\end_inset

 for treatment posts, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}^{j}=1$
\end_inset

 if candidate 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in top 3 of trait 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{h}$
\end_inset

 is number of interviewees.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
