\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Leaver et al (2021): Analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
As we saw above, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $N=18$
\end_inset

 labor markets, so power is a real concern
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exactly which empirical specification has the highest power to test the
 hypotehses above depends on features of the data that are unknown 
\series bold
ex ante
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But we don't want to allow researchers to specification hunt (
\emph on
p
\emph default
-hack) 
\series bold
ex post
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solution: Blinding
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
IPA blinded the data before giving it to the researchers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Researchers explored pre-specified designs in the blinded data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
After updating PAP, researchers received true data and implemented power-maximiz
ing designs
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Solution: Randomization Inference.
 Central limit theorems won't work well with 
\begin_inset Formula $N=18$
\end_inset

 clusters so use RI instead (Imbens & Rubin 2015) which works even in finite
 samples by providing exact inference.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
